This paper investigates the effect of network topology on cooperation in a public goods game, which falls under the category of social networks and game theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Other likely sub-categories include cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory), cs.SOC (Computational Social Science), cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy), and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
